{{Infobox military person | honorific_prefix = | name = Vladimir Perić | native_name = Владимир Перић | birth_date = 28 December 1919 | death_date = 5/6 April 1945 (aged 25) | birth_place = [[Prijepolje]], [[Kingdom of Serbs, Croats and Slovenes]] | death_place = [[Sarajevo]], [[Federal People's Republic of Yugoslavia]] | placeofburial = | image = Vladimir Perić Valter.jpg | nickname = Valter | allegiance = {{flagicon|Democratic Federal Yugoslavia}} [[Yugoslav Partisans]] (1941–45) | serviceyears = 1941–45 | rank = | branch = | commands = Yugoslav Partisans in Sarajevo | unit = | battles = [[World War II in Yugoslavia]] | awards = | death = }} '''Vladimir Perić''' ({{lang-sr-cyr|Владимир Перић}}; 28 December 1919&nbsp;– 5/6 April 1945), best known by the ''[[nom de guerre]]'' '''Valter''', was a [[Yugoslav Partisans|Partisan]] commander in German-occupied [[Sarajevo]] during [[World War II]].
Born in the Serbian town of [[Prijepolje]], he became a member of the [[Communist Party of Yugoslavia]] (KPJ) in 1940. The following year, he joined the Partisans and was appointed deputy political commissar of a Partisan unit in eastern [[Bosnia (region)|Bosnia]] in 1942. In 1943, Perić became secretary of the Sarajevo committee of the KPJ and took charge of anti-sabotage actions in the city in early 1945. While visiting a tobacco factory at midnight on 5–6 April, Perić was killed after a German soldier hurtled a [[hand grenade]] at him. His death made him one of the last Sarajevans killed in World War II.
==Early life== Vladimir Perić was born in the town of [[Prijepolje]] on 28 December 1919. He graduated from a trade school in his hometown and moved to [[Belgrade]] to attend business school. His school years were characterized by constant poverty and he struggled to find work to pay for his education.<ref>{{cite book|editor-last=Stojković|editor-first=Zlatko|year=1975|title=Narodni heroji Jugoslavije|chapter=Perić, Vladimir–Valter|publisher=Mladost|location=Belgrade|url=http://www.titomanija.com.ba/e-knjige/Narodni%20heroji%20Jugoslavije.pdf|p=367}}</ref> From 1938 to 1940, Perić worked at the Mortage Bank ({{lang-sh|Hipotekarna banka}}) in Belgrade. In 1940, he became a member of the [[Communist Party of Yugoslavia]] ({{lang-sh|Komunistička partija Jugoslavije}}; KPJ). Shortly afterwards, he was transferred to the bank's Sarajevo branch.{{sfn|Donia|2006|p=195}}
==World War II== [[File:Axis occupation of Yugoslavia 1941-43.png|thumb|left|A map showing the Axis occupation of Yugoslavia from 1941–43.|alt=map showing the partition of Yugoslavia, 1941–43]] On 6 April 1941, [[Axis powers|Axis]] forces [[Invasion of Yugoslavia|invaded]] Yugoslavia. Poorly equipped and poorly trained, the [[Royal Yugoslav Army]] was quickly defeated. After the invasion, Yugoslavia was dismembered, with the extreme [[Croat]] nationalist and fascist [[Ante Pavelić]], who had been in exile in [[Benito Mussolini]]'s [[Kingdom of Italy|Italy]], being appointed ''[[Poglavnik]]'' (leader) of an [[Ustaše]]-led Croatian state – the [[Independent State of Croatia]] (often called the NDH, from the {{lang-hr|Nezavisna Država Hrvatska}}). The NDH combined almost all of modern-day [[Croatia]], all of modern-day [[Bosnia and Herzegovina]] and parts of modern-day [[Serbia]] into an "Italian-German quasi-protectorate."{{sfn|Tomasevich|2001|p=272}} NDH authorities, led by the [[Ustaše militia]],{{sfn|Tomasevich|2001|pp=397–409}} subsequently implemented genocidal policies against the [[Serb]], [[Jewish]] and [[Romani people|Romani]] population living within the borders of the new state.{{sfn|Hoare|2007|pp=20–24}} As a result, two resistance movements emerged – the royalist and Serb Chetniks, led by [[Colonel]] [[Draža Mihailović]], and the multi-ethnic, [[Communist]] [[Yugoslav Partisans]], led by [[Josip Broz Tito]].{{sfn|Ramet|2006|p=4}}
Perić was only twenty-one years old when the war began.{{sfn|Donia|2006|p=195}} Having become a member of the KPJ before the war, he immediately joined the Partisans.{{sfn|Donia|2006|p=175}} In the spring of 1941, he and other members of the KPJ participated in planning underground resistance operations.{{sfn|Donia|2006|p=195}} Later that year, he and other members of the party appealed for wealthy citizens of Sarajevo to provide food and money to the city's beleaguered Jewish community.{{sfn|Donia|2006|p=175}} As the war progressed, Perić came to be known by the codename ''Valter''.{{sfn|Donia|2006|p=195}} In 1942, Perić participated in actions against German forces in [[Zenica]].{{sfn|Duvnjak|14 March 2009}} That year, he was appointed deputy political commissar of a Partisan unit in eastern [[Bosnia (region)|Bosnia]], holding that position until the following year,{{sfn|Donia|2006|p=195}} when he participated in Partisan actions against German troops in the city of [[Tuzla]].{{sfn|Duvnjak|14 March 2009}} That year, regional leaders named him secretary of the Sarajevo committee of the KPJ, giving him the task of reconstituting the party's organization in the city. Perić responded by encouraging the Partisans to recruit in urban areas and reconstructed the KPJ to increase its support for the Partisans by providing further personnel, supplies and intelligence.{{sfn|Donia|2006|p=195}}
In June 1944, Perić took on the role of directing the formation, training and deployment of Partisan strike groups (known as "fivesomes", or ''Petorke'') operating in Sarajevo and its outskirts.{{sfn|Donia|2006|p=200}}
===Death=== [[File:Vladimir "Valter" Perić plaque in Sarajevo.jpg|thumb|Plaque in Sarajevo dedicated to Perić.]] The liberation of Sarajevo was organized by a powerful network of underground anti-German movements led by Perić.{{sfn|Hoare|2007|p=306}} By early 1945 the Partisans engaged in a campaign against German saboteurs, with Perić being personally responsible for anti-sabotage actions in Sarajevo. In early April, he visited the city's main post office and electrical generating plant to ensure that they had not been sabotaged by withdrawing German forces. While visiting a tobacco factory at midnight on 5–6 April, Perić was killed after a German soldier hurtled a [[hand grenade]] at him. Perić's death made him one of the last Sarajevans killed in World War II.{{sfn|Donia|2006|p=200}} At around the same time as his death, most German soldiers in Sarajevo had either left the city or were captured by the Partisans.{{sfn|Donia|2006|pp=205–206}} On 9 April the KPJ formed a new local committee in Sarajevo, appointing new members to take the places left behind by Perić and other rebels killed while fighting the Germans in the previous week.{{sfn|Greble|2011|p=230}} Perić's funeral occurred the next day at a Christian cemetery that was decorated with banners written in [[Serbian Cyrillic]]. The funeral procession was led by two [[Serbian Orthodox]] priests and a deacon and was followed by men carrying large crosses in accordance with Serbian Orthodox tradition, with most of those in attendance being Orthodox Serbs.{{sfn|Greble|2011|p=231}}
==Legacy== The [[Partisan film]] ''[[Walter Defends Sarajevo]]'' ({{lang-sh|Valter brani Sarajevo}}), released in 1972, is a fictionalized portrayal of Perić's activities during World War II which ends with a statement in favour of unity when a SS officer realizes at the end of the movie that he was fighting not just a single partisan but an entire city ("You see that city? That's Walter!). In 1992, anti-nationalist and anti-war demonstrators in [[Sarajevo]] evoked Perić's memory as a sign of inter-ethnic tolerance prior to the outbreak of the [[Bosnian War]];{{sfn|Donia|2006|p=200}} demonstrators bore stickers that read "I am Walter" and one anti-war movement was even named after Perić.{{sfn|Hoare|2007|p=363}}
